    <text>
        <body>
            <div type="letter">
                <pb n="1" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1828_12_07_page01.jpg"/>
                <opener>
                    <dateline>
                        <placeName ref="./Placeography.xml#Edgeworthstown_IE"/>Edgeworths Town
                        <date when="1828-12-07">Dec<hi rend="superscript">r</hi>. 7<hi rend="superscript">h</hi> 1828</date></dateline>
                    <salute>Dear Sir</salute>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    I send you a new translation of the<lb/>
                    <title ref="./Workography.xml#Agame2">Agamemnon of <persName ref="./Personography.xml#Aesch1"><choice><orig>Aschylus</orig><reg>Aeschylus</reg></choice></persName></title> - by a <persName ref="./Personography.xml#HarfJ1"><choice><orig>gentle-<lb/>
                    man</orig><reg>gentleman</reg></choice></persName> who is a friend of mine -<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    I am no scholar, and cannot<lb/>
                    <del>therefore</del> give you any opinion <choice><orig>con-<lb/>
                    cerning</orig><reg>concerning</reg></choice> the <hi rend="underline">fidelity</hi> of the translation<lb/>
                    from the Greek - on that subject you<lb/>
                    must consult some greek scholar<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="superscript">a</hi> But I can give you a decided<lb/>
                    opinion concerning its merit as to<lb/>
                    English composition - It reads like<lb/>
                    an original - I had many years ago<lb/>
                    read <persName ref="./Personography.xml#PottR1">Potter's</persName> translation of the <title ref="./Workography.xml#Trage1"><choice><orig>Agamem<lb/>
                    -non</orig><reg>Agamemnon</reg></choice></title> &amp; would compare the impression<lb/>
                    which that &amp; the present translation<lb/>
                    made upon my mind - I have since<lb/>
                    compared all the principal passages<lb/>
                    and the <unclear>choruses</unclear> - I have no doubt<lb/>
                    of the superiority of that which I now<lb/>
                    send you - I have also compared it with<lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <pb n="2" facs="Edgeworth_NLS_42180_1828_12_07_page02.jpg"/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#SymmJ1">Symmons</persName> translation made 3 or 4<lb/>
                    years ago - the result has been the<lb/>
                    same conviction that the superiority<lb/>
                    rests with the last. <lb/>
                </p>
                <p>
                    The author's own preface says all<lb/>
                    that is to be said of the reasons for <choice><orig>sup<lb/>
                    posing</orig><reg>supposing</reg></choice> that the public would be glad<lb/>
                    to have a new translation if better than the old<lb/>
                    ones - The only questions that remains<lb/>
                    are plainly, would you like to have this?<lb/>
                    And what would you give for it?<lb/>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    I am <choice><orig>D<hi rend="superscript">r</hi></orig><reg>Dear</reg></choice> Sir<lb/>
                    Yours sincerely<lb/>
                    <persName ref="./Personography.xml#EdgeM1">Maria Edgeworth</persName><lb/>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
        <back> </back>
